context: Santa Monica was long inhabited by the <a1_0><b9_0>Tongva<b9_0/><a1_0/> people. Santa Monica was called <a0_0>Kecheek<a0_0/> in the <b5_0>Tongva<b5_0/> language. The first non-indigenous group to set foot in the area was the party of explorer <a2_0>Gaspar de Portolà<a2_0/>, who camped near the present day intersection of Barrington and Ohio Avenues on <a4_0><b7_0>August 3, <b6_0><b8_0>1769<b8_0/><b7_0/><b6_0/><a4_0/>. There are two different versions of the naming of the city. One says that it was named in honor of the feast day of Saint Monica (mother of Saint Augustine), but her feast day is actually <a3_0>May 4<a3_0/>. Another version says that it was named by Juan Crespí on account of a pair of springs, the Kuruvungna Springs (Serra Springs), that were reminiscent of the tears that Saint Monica shed over her son's early impiety.
